00:07:15.179 --> 00:07:21.339
Okay. One area of interest in many companies is how can we use predictive models to help

00:07:21.339 --> 00:07:26.299
reduce employee attrition? And if you're not familiar with the term attrition, that is

00:07:26.299 --> 00:07:34.179
a metric that we use in HR to measure the rate at which employees are leaving the company.

00:07:34.179 --> 00:07:39.980
We have three main turnover categories that we look at and which you also might want to

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:44.140
look at at your company in terms of determining which areas you might want to focus on for

00:07:44.140 --> 00:07:53.059
your first attrition project. One is involuntary dismissals. The other could be voluntary separations

00:07:53.059 --> 00:07:59.899
or voluntary turnover that is related to retirement. And we could also have voluntary turnover

00:08:00.019 --> 00:08:04.619
that is not related to retirement where those employees, instead of leaving the workforce,

00:08:04.619 --> 00:08:08.940
they are leaving the company to go work somewhere else.

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:13.820
And we found it very helpful in looking at our attrition projects to also look at different

00:08:13.820 --> 00:08:18.980
employee segments and choose the ones that are appropriate for your company. But we found

00:08:18.980 --> 00:08:24.019
helpful to look at frontline employees who work directly with our customers, knowledge

00:08:24.019 --> 00:08:31.220
workers and executives or senior leadership. For each of these groups, then we consider

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:36.500
the degree of difficulty of the project versus the potential benefit we may realize in terms

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:44.340
of return on investment from achieved from reducing attrition. For employees that voluntarily

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:48.020
leave due to retirement, meaning they're leaving the workforce and aren't planning to go to

00:08:48.020 --> 00:08:53.979
work for another company, the degree of difficulty in reducing attrition is fairly low. However,

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:59.580
the potential benefit is low to medium due to this being a smaller percentage of our employees.

00:09:01.500 --> 00:09:06.539
However, when you're looking at voluntary, that's attrition that's not related to retirement.

00:09:06.539 --> 00:09:12.140
For frontline employees, the degree of difficulty is about medium. It's higher than those for

00:09:12.140 --> 00:09:20.219
retirements. But your return on investment is very high. With executives or senior leadership,

00:09:20.219 --> 00:09:25.580
the degree of difficulty is higher than those for frontline workers and your return on investment

00:09:25.580 --> 00:09:31.099
or potential benefit is lower, simply due to this being a smaller population of our workforce.

00:09:31.979 --> 00:09:37.260
And with knowledge workers, your degree of difficulty is higher than those for frontline

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:42.619
employees. But your potential benefit is also just as high as you'll see with frontline employees.

00:09:43.659 --> 00:09:47.659
For those that are involuntarily dismissed, your degree of difficulty is higher.

00:09:48.619 --> 00:09:54.059
And your potential benefit is low because this is typically a very small percentage of the population.

00:09:58.380 --> 00:10:04.780
As you're continuing to plan an attrition project, we have a project roadmap that we found very

00:10:04.780 --> 00:10:12.780
helpful in consisting of four steps. Our overall goal is to identify the items that we can change

00:10:12.859 --> 00:10:16.539
and work with leadership in the business unit to help implement those changes

00:10:17.099 --> 00:10:24.140
with the overall objective of reducing attrition. So our first step is identifying those areas of

00:10:24.140 --> 00:10:29.340
the business unit where we have high turnover and also a good return on investment if we can

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:35.099
reduce attrition. We then conducted research and developed predictive models to identify what those

00:10:35.099 --> 00:10:41.580
attrition drivers are, then developed interventions on the variables that we can impact or change in

00:10:41.580 --> 00:10:47.340
the business unit, and we selected certain locations where we implemented those changes.

00:10:47.979 --> 00:10:52.700
And then over time, we measured the impact to attrition for those locations to see

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:58.219
how much impact we could achieve if we implemented them nationwide. And from there,

00:10:58.219 --> 00:11:03.979
we chose which items we wanted to change and roll them out throughout the entire country

00:11:03.979 --> 00:11:07.419
or throughout the entire business unit, whichever is applicable to your company.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:13.500
In developing a project focused on attrition, it's also very helpful to segment your employee

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:18.539
population to help control for any latent variables. And some areas that you might want

00:11:18.539 --> 00:11:23.820
to consider looking at could include employee tenure, where you're trying to figure out

00:11:23.820 --> 00:11:28.539
where is your higher attrition rates. Is that found among new employees or more established

00:11:28.539 --> 00:11:34.059
employees? You may look at management status, non-management versus management,

00:11:34.059 --> 00:11:39.500
employees, perhaps looking at supervisors versus individual contributors and see where you might

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:47.500
have the most impact. Job type is a key one where grouping similar jobs together helps minimize the

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:51.900
impact of latent variables. For example, our technicians who are working in the field,

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:56.619
maintaining our network, are doing a very different job from, say, our sales associates

00:11:56.619 --> 00:12:01.580
and retail stores. Doing separate attrition projects focused on each of those different

00:12:01.580 --> 00:12:06.059
Doing separate attrition projects focused on each of these job groups separately

00:12:06.059 --> 00:12:11.739
helps us make sure we're getting good results from our predictive models to determine what are the

00:12:11.739 --> 00:12:17.419
attrition drivers for each of those job groups. And you might also consider looking at results

00:12:17.419 --> 00:12:22.859
of your employee engagement surveys to see how attitudes impact your willingness to stay.

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:29.020
And just like job type, you might also consider full-time versus part-time,

00:12:29.020 --> 00:12:34.059
or if you have shift work at your company, consider that as well. Grouping those different

00:12:34.059 --> 00:12:39.500
types of employees together may also help improve any attrition project or predictive models that

00:12:39.500 --> 00:12:47.580
you are building. Any questions before I move on? I'm seeing quite a few questions starting to come

00:12:47.580 --> 00:12:56.059
through Slido, and let me jump over. There were a few about KPIs, and one was what are the most

00:12:56.059 --> 00:13:04.460
important people analytics KPIs at AT&T? Oh, we have several, and depending on what are the

00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:10.780
needs of the business, we develop them, but the one focused here in this case for an attrition

00:13:10.780 --> 00:13:18.380
project is there is a standard attrition KPI that all companies measure in HR, and that is the

00:13:18.380 --> 00:13:24.219
number of employees that separate divided by your average headcount for a specific time period that

00:13:24.219 --> 00:13:28.940
you are measuring, and that will give you, you multiply that result by 100, and that will give

00:13:28.940 --> 00:13:35.340
you an attrition rate. We always express it as a percentage, and if you're looking at tenure groups,

00:13:35.340 --> 00:13:41.099
you may look at your number of employees who separated in that specific tenure group divided

00:13:41.099 --> 00:13:46.059
by your average headcount in that tenure group to get a more specific measurement for each of the

00:13:46.059 --> 00:13:53.179
tenure groups that you're looking at, for example. Thank you. Another question, maybe I'll take

00:13:53.179 --> 00:14:00.380
three questions or so right here, but one was do you distinguish between attrition versus

00:14:00.380 --> 00:14:03.419
turnover based on the position being backfilled or not?

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:11.419
Most of the time we measure attrition in terms of whether it's involuntary or voluntary,

00:14:11.419 --> 00:14:18.619
meaning the employee chose to resign and are either going elsewhere or perhaps if they're

00:14:18.619 --> 00:14:23.580
voluntary and they're also retiring, and we know that for a fact, we might look at attrition just

00:14:23.580 --> 00:14:28.299
for those that are not retiring, but we don't measure it in terms of whether or not we're

00:14:28.299 --> 00:14:32.219
backfilling the position. In that, in the attrition calculation itself, we don't.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:42.619
Great, thank you. There was one other question I see that just came in on YouTube, and I'll pull

