who stayed and left in the past and controlling for all of the things that are included in that

00:18:31.979 --> 00:18:38.380
model together in one place. We can then interpret the results of those models and determine which

00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:45.020
items are associated with a high probability of leading the company

00:18:45.579 --> 00:18:50.219
compared to other items in that model. So interpretation of the model, for those of you

00:18:50.219 --> 00:18:54.859
who are data scientists, you may be familiar, some models are more easily interpreted than others.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:59.739
In people analytics, interpretation of the model is the most important.

00:19:02.380 --> 00:19:06.859
And here's an example of why it's most important, because when you are later communicating with

00:19:06.859 --> 00:19:13.660
business leaders on the results of that model, they want to know which variables are associated

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:19.819
with high probability of leading, as well as which ones are associated with our ability to influence

00:19:19.819 --> 00:19:25.739
or change those items. And this type of visual is just one possible example of how you may present

00:19:25.739 --> 00:19:32.140
that data to leadership to let them know which areas that we might want to focus on where we're

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:36.060
going to get a high return on investment for making those changes.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:41.420
Are there any questions about predictive modeling for attrition?

00:19:52.300 --> 00:19:59.260
Okay, another area where we found very helpful is forecasting workforce changes. And for this

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:04.859
types of forecasting, we have been using time series predictive models. If you're not familiar

00:20:04.859 --> 00:20:10.780
with time series models, these are models where you are measuring something over a period of time.

00:20:10.780 --> 00:20:16.780
This graph on the right side of the page will give you an example, not specific to AT&T, but just to

00:20:16.780 --> 00:20:21.180
show you when you're looking at time series models, oftentimes you have to consider whether there's

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:27.260
any seasonality in the data. So you can see on this example, there's an increase in value around

00:20:27.260 --> 00:20:32.060
the beginning of every year. And the predictive part of our model, which is shaded in blue,

00:20:32.060 --> 00:20:37.900
is also forecasting an increase at the beginning of each year. So this is the type of model that

00:20:37.900 --> 00:20:45.099
we have found very helpful on some cases for workforce planning. One area that we've used this

00:20:45.099 --> 00:20:53.260
often is estimating the pandemic's impact on our workforce in 2020 and 2021. As each variant of the

00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:59.500
COVID virus spread throughout the U.S., we were able to make rough estimates of employee absences

00:20:59.500 --> 00:21:05.099
that we might see in different geographic areas. And that helped us ensure that we could do some

00:21:05.099 --> 00:21:10.540
planning, maybe even temporarily moving employees to other locations to help ensure that our customer

00:21:10.540 --> 00:21:17.099
needs continue to be met during the pandemic. We've also found changes like many companies,

00:21:17.099 --> 00:21:22.939
employee attrition rates have been very different in both 2020, 2021, even throughout this year.

00:21:23.579 --> 00:21:29.339
And we've been using some models to try and predict our future changes in employee attrition

00:21:29.339 --> 00:21:37.819
rates that we might see, which then fed into our strategic talent acquisition plans to try and

00:21:37.819 --> 00:21:44.540
determine how we needed to change or backfill positions as people left. And our third area

00:21:44.540 --> 00:21:50.380
that we found this very helpful is in our future planning. As our plans for our product portfolio

00:21:50.380 --> 00:21:56.060
changes over the next few years, we've been using models to try and predict how our workforce may

00:21:56.060 --> 00:22:01.579
change in the future, both through voluntary separations or employees moving into other job

00:22:01.579 --> 00:22:08.780
titles in order to give us a feel for how we may plan for skills and job titles that may be needed

