00:24:29.579 --> 00:24:37.660
Okay. So our last area where we found data science to be very helpful is analyzing employee survey

00:24:37.660 --> 00:24:43.500
comments. And I mentioned in our surveys, we sometimes ask employees to give us feedback about

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:49.739
AT&T where they're allowed to type anything that they would like to say. And when of course you're

00:24:49.739 --> 00:24:55.099
looking at thousands of comments, it's hard to summarize what are people talking about. So we

00:24:55.099 --> 00:25:01.500
found topic modeling to be very helpful in this area. The modeling approach that we use for those

00:25:01.500 --> 00:25:07.739
of you that are familiar with text analytics is late and Derek lay allocation. And this allows us

00:25:07.739 --> 00:25:15.500
without going into the math and a lot of detail, this allows us to group together certain comments

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:21.500
based on the keywords that employees use in those comments. We take out some of the common words like

00:25:21.500 --> 00:25:27.339
the and of, because every comment is going to have those words in them. And that then reduces

00:25:27.339 --> 00:25:33.660
down the comments to the unique words that exist in each of them. From there, we can then summarize

00:25:33.660 --> 00:25:39.739
those topics. So here's an example of how topic modeling may work. And this is just based on

00:25:39.739 --> 00:25:45.339
industry data because we figure most companies are going to see comments about these topics.

00:25:46.300 --> 00:25:52.619
So you can see here on the left, I've got two lists of words here. And these are examples of

00:25:53.260 --> 00:25:58.699
comments, words that are coming from various comments from employees. And you can see there's

00:25:58.699 --> 00:26:03.500
two entirely different lists. Advancement, opportunity, career, promotion is entirely

00:26:03.500 --> 00:26:11.020
different from pay, retirement, salary, raises, insurance, and so forth. So from there, we can then

00:26:11.020 --> 00:26:17.660
decide our topic for the items on the left are more focused on career growth. And these items

00:26:17.660 --> 00:26:23.819
on the right are focused more on pay and benefits related comments. From there, we can continue this

00:26:23.819 --> 00:26:30.699
process to label all of our different topics that show up in the comments. And that then allows us

00:26:30.699 --> 00:26:35.979
to prepare some summaries for executives to let them know which areas are people commenting on

00:26:35.979 --> 00:26:41.339
the most, what are the biggest concerns of our employees. And from there, they can decide what

00:26:41.339 --> 00:26:46.780
actions they want to take to try and change things at AT&T based on the feedback that we've received.

00:26:48.540 --> 00:26:54.060
Another area in text analytics that we found very helpful is we often get questions from management

00:26:54.060 --> 00:27:00.060
regarding the sentiment of those topics or the comments in general. Are they positive or negative?

00:27:00.699 --> 00:27:07.339
So in that case, we've been using lexicon-based algorithms. There are two general purpose lexicons

00:27:07.339 --> 00:27:12.939
available in both R and Python. One is AFIN and BING, and these are developed by researchers

00:27:13.500 --> 00:27:18.140
who have examined a lot of comments and determined that certain words are

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:25.260
representing a positive or negative sentiment in those words or in those comments. However,

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:31.500
for people analytics cases where employees are commenting about their jobs or awards or benefits,

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:37.420
we found it helpful to customize these lexicons to give us a better understanding of the sentiment

00:27:37.420 --> 00:27:44.540
expressed in work-related comments or job-related comments. So we've removed some words from the

00:27:44.540 --> 00:27:50.780
standard lexicons, and those words are listed here on the left. And you can see things like

00:27:50.780 --> 00:27:57.020
pay and work. They're more general topics of comments about pay and work, but what we really

00:27:57.020 --> 00:28:03.420
want to know is what is their sentiment about pay and work, for example. So we found it's easier to

00:28:03.420 --> 00:28:08.140
remove those words, and then we can get a better, more accurate understanding of the sentiment of

00:28:08.140 --> 00:28:14.699
their comments. And then you may find, looking at the comments in general, you may find there's

00:28:14.699 --> 00:28:19.739
words that should be added, maybe even some that are unique to your company or your industry,

00:28:20.459 --> 00:28:24.939
that would help give you an even better understanding of sentiment. And some words that

00:28:24.939 --> 00:28:29.339
don't exist in the general purpose lexicons, like burnout. We're seeing a lot of articles about

00:28:29.339 --> 00:28:35.739
employees feeling burnout these days. Micromanage, which seems to exist in almost any company.

00:28:35.739 --> 00:28:40.859
These are things that you may consider adding to your custom sentiment lexicon to help give you a

00:28:40.859 --> 00:28:45.660
better understanding of your sentiment in these employee-based comments.

00:28:47.979 --> 00:28:53.819
What we do overall in sentiment analysis is then from that, once you've customized your lexicon,

00:28:53.819 --> 00:28:58.619
we apply that to the comments and try and measure the number of positive words and the number of

00:28:58.619 --> 00:29:04.540
negative words that appear in each comment. And we take the positive words minus the negative words

00:29:04.540 --> 00:29:10.459
and give us a general comment score so that we can see, overall, is that comment mostly positive or

00:29:10.459 --> 00:29:17.500
is it mostly negative? And from there, you can give management an understanding of, are the

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:23.339
comments about a specific topic more positive or negative? Or even just overall, among all of the

00:29:23.339 --> 00:29:29.979
comments that employees make, are they mostly positive or negative? Are there any questions

